#######################################################
################ Serial Physical Notes  ###############
#######################################################


(I) FreeBSD14-3 motherboard USB port (any random port)
(II) USBA 2.0 <--> Î¼-USB male
(III) digilent PmodUARTUSB adapter (blinks a red LED briefly when you connect)
(IV) Dupont female to female connections
~~~~~ Pinout Format ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
[Pmod pin #, pmod pin fct, wire color, Pine64 connector, connector pin #, Pine64 FCT]
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
[2, RXD, RED, 'EXP', 7, "UART0_TX/PB8_TX"]
[3, TXD, BLU, 'EXP', 8, "PB8_RX"]
[5, GND, GRN, 'EXP', 9, "GND"]


Hop on the terminal and identify the UART device on your host machine

$:  `dmesg | grep -i ucom`
$:  `ls /dev/cuaU*`

^^^the above step screwed up because i grabbed a random microUSB for charging
my phones and it didn't enumerate when I did `usbconfig list`, changed the 
cable and lo & behold it enumerated.


0 fran.sys ~/code/lameOS > kldstat | egrep ' ucom| uftdi'
18    1 0xffffffff832c4000     85e0 uftdi.ko
19    1 0xffffffff832cd000     4e10 ucom.ko


0 fran.sys ~/code/lameOS > ls -l /dev/cuaU* /dev/ttyU* 2>/dev/null
crw-rw----  1 uucp dialer 0x18d Aug 10 13:59 /dev/cuaU0
crw-rw----  1 uucp dialer 0x18e Aug 10 13:59 /dev/cuaU0.init
crw-rw----  1 uucp dialer 0x18f Aug 10 13:59 /dev/cuaU0.lock
crw-------  1 root wheel  0x18a Aug 10 13:59 /dev/ttyU0
crw-------  1 root wheel  0x18b Aug 10 13:59 /dev/ttyU0.init
crw-------  1 root wheel  0x18c Aug 10 13:59 /dev/ttyU0.lock


##########################################################
####                                                  ####
####  Command to communicate over PmodUSBUART Device  ####
####                                                  ####
##########################################################

sudo picocom -b 115200 --flow n --imap lfcrlf --omap crlf /dev/cuaU0


























